Introduction¶

For the purpose of the project I will be using the csv file containing data collected from Brazil about whether or not patients showed up to their medical appointments.

The description provided for this data set "This dataset collects information from 100k medical appointments in Brazil and is focused on the question of whether or not patients show up for their appointment. A number of characteristics about the patient are included in each row.

  • ‘ScheduledDay’ tells us on what day the patient set up their appointment.
  • ‘Neighborhood’ indicates the location of the hospital.
  • ‘Scholarship’ indicates whether or not the patient is enrolled in Brasilian welfare program Bolsa Família.
  • 'No-show' column says ‘No’ if the patient showed up to their appointment, and ‘Yes’ if they did not show up."

The question that this analysis will help answer is "What factors make a patient more likely to show up for an appointment?".

The dependent Factor is No-show status The independent Factors that are going to be investigated are Age, Scholarship and Received SMS

Data Cleaning¶

The Data set has no duplicates or missing values to be cleaned or dropped

While exploring the data using the describe function minimum age was (-1) which is an invalid entry. All column names need to be in lower case and multiple words should be separated by for easy readability. the dash in no-show will be changed to an as well. Also The Hipertesion and Handcap are misspelled and need to be renamed.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

After completing data cleaning and filtering, I'll move on to the exploration phase of the analysis. The objective is to answer the research questions stated in the Introduction section through statistical computations and data visualization. To ensure that my approach is comprehensive, I will examine one variable at a time and then proceed to investigate the relationships between variables. Specifically, I will compare the No-show variable with each of the three variables of interest - Age, Scholarship, and SMS received - before analyzing their interrelationships.

Q1 Which age group had the most number of missed appointments?¶

First I will create bin edges to cut the data into groups

In [16]:
# create bin edge to cut the age data into groups
bins = [-1, 12, 18, 30, 50, 60, 70, 80, 90, 100, 110, 120]

#labels for the age groups
labels = ['child', 'teen', 'young adult', 'middle age', '50s', '60s', '70s', '80s', '90s', '100s', '110s']
In [17]:
#create age_group column
df['age_group'] = pd.cut(df['age'], bins, labels=labels)

#create masks for show vs no_show status
no_show = df.no_show == 'Yes'
show = df.no_show == 'No'
In [26]:
#create a bar chart to visualize the data and the correlation between having scholarship and the no-show status
df.scholarship[show].hist(label = 'showed for appointment');
df.scholarship[no_show].hist(label = 'missed appointment');
plt.title('Number of missed appointments vs Scholarship status')
plt.xlabel('Scholarship Status')
plt.ylabel('Number of patients')
plt.legend();

By grouping scholarship status along with no-show status using the groupby function and further visualizing the data using bar chart it seems that more patients without a scholarship showed up for their appointment than patients who have a scholarship.

Based of the data generated 90% of the patients do not have a scholarship and out of those patients 80% showed up for their appointments. On the other hand, Only 10% of the patients had a scholarship and out of those patients 76% showed up for their appointments.

By analyzing the gathered data, it seems that there's no correlation between having a scholarship and a patient showing up for their appointment. Since a higher percentage of patients showed up for their appointments without having a scholarship.

Based of the data generated 68% of the patients did not recieve an sms and out of those patients 83% showed up for their appointments. On the other hand, 32% of the patients received an sms and out of those patients 72% showed up for their appointments.

By analyzing the gathered data, it seems that there's no correlation between receiving an sms and a patient showing up for their appointment. Since a almost an equal percentage of patients showed up for their appointments whether they received an sms or not.

Conclusions¶

Throughout this data analysis project, I investigated this dataset to understand the factors that influence whether or not a patient shows up for their medical appointment. My findings suggest that the age of the patient is a significant factor, with patients in the middle age group (30-50 years old) having the highest number of missed appointments.

Additionally, I found that there was no significant correlation between a patient having a scholarship or receiving an SMS reminder and whether or not they showed up for their appointment. These findings indicate that other factors may be at play in determining whether or not patients attend their appointments, and further research is necessary to understand the underlying causes of missed appointments in this demographic.

It's important to note that this analysis has its limitations. I did not perform any statistical tests, so my conclusions are based solely on observed correlations in the data. The findings of this study provide valuable insights for healthcare providers to develop targeted strategies to improve appointment scheduling and patient communication, but additional research is necessary to fully understand the factors that influence attendance rates.
